[00:00.32]Passage 48. | 第48节
[00:02.37]I have known very few writers, but those I have known and whom I respect, | 我认识的作家不多，但我认识并尊重他们，
[00:06.51]confess at once that they have little idea where they are going when they first set pen to paper. | 他们立刻承认，当他们第一次提笔时，他们几乎不知道自己要写什么。
[00:12.16]They have a character, perhaps two. | 他们有一个个性，也许是两个。
[00:14.77]They are in that condition of eager discomfort which passes for inspiration. | 他们处于一种渴望不安的状态，这种不安被视为灵感。
[00:19.98]All admit radical changes of destination once the journey has begun. | 一旦旅程开始，所有人都承认目的地会有根本性的改变。
[00:24.47]One, to my certain knowledge, spent nine months on a novel about Kashmir, | 据我所知，有一位作家花九个月写了一部关于克什米尔的小说，
[00:29.35]then reset the whole thing in the Scottish Highlands. | 然后把整个故事背景重新设定在苏格兰高地。
[00:32.93]I never heard of anyone making a skeleton, as we were taught at school. | 我从未听说有人像我们在学校学的那样先搭好骨架。
[00:37.81]In the breaking and remaking, in the timing, interweaving, beginning afresh, | 在打破和重塑中，在时机把握中，在交织中，在重新开始中，
[00:42.79]the writer comes to discern things in his material which were not consciously in his mind when he began. | 作家开始在自己的素材中发现一些他开始时并未意识到的东西。
[00:49.46]This organic process, often leading to moments of extraordinary self-discovery, | 这种有机过程，常常带来非凡的自我发现时刻，
[00:54.91]is of an indescribable fascination. | 具有一种难以言喻的魅力。
[00:59.39]A blurred image appears; he adds a brushstroke and another, and it is gone. | 模糊的意象出现，他添上一笔又一笔，然后它消失了。
[01:04.14]But something was there, and he will not rest till he has captured it. | 但有些东西曾存在，他不会停歇，直到他捕捉到它。
[01:08.61]Sometimes the yeast within a writer outlives a book he has written. | 有时，作家内心的“酵母”比他写出的书更长寿。
[01:12.78]I have heard of writers who read nothing but their own books; | 我听说过有些作家除了自己的书什么都不读；
[01:16.14]like adolescents they stand before the mirror and still cannot fathom the exact outline of the vision before them. | 就像青少年一样，他们站在镜子前，仍然无法完全领会他们眼前景象的精确轮廓。
[01:23.36]For the same reason, writers talk interminably about their own books, | 基于同样的原因，作家们没完没了地谈论自己的作品，
[01:27.42]wrinkling out hidden meanings, superimposing new ones, begging response from those around them. | 挖掘出隐藏的意义，叠加新的含义，并向周围的人寻求回应。
[01:34.39]Of course, a writer doing this is misunderstood. | 当然，一个这样做事的作家是会被误解的。
[01:37.66]He might as well try to explain a crime or a love affair. | 他倒不如去解释一桩罪行或一段风流韵事。
[01:41.38]He is also, incidentally, an unforgivable bore. | 顺便说一句，他也是一个不可饶恕的无聊之人。
[01:45.92]This temptation to cover the distance between himself and the reader, | 这种试图缩短自己与读者之间距离的诱惑，
[01:49.61]to study his image in the sight of those who do not know him, can be his undoing. | 在不认识他的人眼中审视自己的形象，可能正是他的败笔。
[01:54.21]He has begun to write to please. | 他开始为了取悦他人而写作。
[01:57.48]A young English writer made the pertinent observation a year or two back | 一位年轻的英国作家在一两年前曾做过一个中肯的观察，
[02:02.50]that the talent goes into the first draft, and the art into the drafts that follow. | 他说，天赋在于初稿，而艺术则在于后续的修订。
[02:07.45]For this reason, also the writer, like any other artist, has no resting place, | 因此，作家也像其他艺术家一样，没有安身之所，
[02:12.51]no crowd or movement in which he may take comfort, | 没有可以让他感到慰藉的人群或潮流，
[02:16.03]no judgment from outside which can replace the judgment from within. | 没有来自外界的评判可以取代内心的评判。
[02:20.30]A writer makes order out of the anarchy of his heart. | 作家从内心的混沌中创造秩序。
[02:23.75]He submits himself to a more ruthless discipline than any critic dreamed of. | 他使自己服从一种比任何评论家所梦想的都更无情的纪律。
[02:29.74]And when he flirts with fame, he's taking time off from living with himself, | 当他追逐名利时，他是在从与自己共处中偷闲，
[02:34.31]from the search for what his world contains at its inmost point. | 从探寻他的世界在其最深处包含着什么的过程中抽身。
